entry.title: assistant: Handle Launcher back action
entry.content:
In the AppList bubble view, the AssistantVisibility is not synced with

the visibility of the `assistant_page` in the Lancher when back action

is triggered. This causes a problem that Assistant thinks it is visible,

but it is not, then Assistant UI will not show again.



The bug is only in clamshell mode. In the tablet mode, this sync is done

by calling OnAppListPageChanged() in ContentsView::ActivePageChanged().



The fix is to explicitly call AssistantUiController::ShowUi/CloseUi when

show/hide `assistant_page` in Launcher.



Bug: b/309551206

Test: Added new browser test: browser_tests --gtest_filter=*AppListIph*

entry.content:
Fixes a bug where enabling GM3 for ChromeOS Ash users, might cause their browser to crash.



Since ChromeOS Ash restarts the browser, flags storage should be updated according to the profile and not the local browser process i.e. `flags_storage = std::make_unique(

original_profile->GetPrefs(), service);`

instead of

`std::unique_ptr flags_storage =

std::make_unique(

g_browser_process->local_state());`

entry.title: Update printing browser tests for system print API variations
entry.content:
The XPS print pipeline for Windows has significant differences compared

to how a print document is handled when printing using GDI. Prepare

for tests to be able to cover both cases by including a platform print

API variation for the test suite parameters.



Note that this CL is a mechanical change in that it does not cause new

tests to be run for XPS. The same number and type of tests which ran

previously still run with this change. Follow-on changes will include

the XPS variations to increase test coverage.



Since XPS platform calls are not allowed from the browser process,

use of testing::Combine() is avoided for automatically generating the

new platform print API testing combinations. A local helper method to

generate valid combinations is used instead.



Apply a naming convention for the generation of strings used for test

suffixes. Functions which take a testing::TestParamInfo<> parameter

are generating the complete suffix, and thus have names which end with

"TestSuffix()". Other functions that take variation parameters are

helpers for making the test suffix, and thus have names that just end

with "String()".



For platforms other than Windows, a current placeholder of platform

print API is identified as CUPS. This generally matches the API used

by the other desktop platforms for which these tests are run. That is,

no distinction is made for whether IPP is used for CUPS.

entry.title: Support redundant response start in PageTimingMetricsSender.
entry.content:
PageTimingMetricsSender::DidStartResponse() can be invoked multiple

times with the same resource id, despite the long-standing DCHECK

suggesting that it doesn't happen (see bug for repro). Prior to

crrev.com/c/4321469, when that happened, the `PageResourceDataUse`

instance already in `page_resource_data_use_` was reused (emplace()

no-ops if the element already exist). Since crrev.com/c/4321469,

the existing `PageResourceDataUse` was deleted and replaced with

a new one. This could result in a dangling pointer in

`modified_resources_`. This CL solves the issue by making

`InsertPageResourceDataUse()` no-op if there is already an entry

with the given id in `page_resource_data_use_`.

entry.title: Revert "[LCPP] Call TimingPredictor fallback at window.onload or later LCP"
entry.content:
This reverts commit b05342ab322925f3d7dac43fa6ff7bc60a030a83.



Reason for revert: Fails lcp_critical_path_predictor/timing_predictor_fallback_nohit.php failing "blink_web_tests on Ubuntu-20.04" failing on builder "chromium/ci/WebKit Linux MSAN".



Original change's description:

> [LCPP] Call TimingPredictor fallback at window.onload or later LCP

>

> LCP Critical Path Predictor(LCPP) learns and predicts what element

> would be LCP in the next loading.

> LCP TimingPredictor is a callback API that occurs if a LCP

> element is painted and predicted as actual LCP(LCP can be reported

> twice or more in a load usually.)

> This API would be used to delay P2 tasks to improve the actual LCP

> timing(or this is our Core Web Vital metric).

> Design Doc(google internal):

> https://docs.google.com/document/d/1V5PFwVTDonJ1RE52ZI5WGRihn07atHLApnIWsZ3fgfM/edit?pli=1&resourcekey=0-6we9zT_a97B6ZH0jRalL3g

>

> However there are cases that callback is never called or too late.

> Then, this CL implements the fallback algorithm

> There are 2 cases:

> 1. At window.onload, LCP occurs multiply before window.onload but no

> LCP prediction was hit. Call the fallback at this timing.

> 2. No LCP occur before window.onload. Call the fallback when the first

> LCP occurs after that. There are several factors delay the first LCP

> (resource fetch, paint, visible element is put after onload, etc.)

>

> This CL also move the callback implementation from Document to

> LCPCriticalPathPredictor to clarify the ownership.

>

Removing the trigger source from AED::DidAcceptSuggestion means that

it must always be provided in the AED::OnQuery call. There're 3 places

where we must check that it happens:



* AutofillExternalDelegate: trigger source is always provided the to

AED in the BrowserAutofillManager.

* iOS AutofillAgent: trigger source is always provided in the agent

by calling the AutofillManager::OnAskForValueToFill.

* AwAutofillClient: trigger source is guaranteed to be provided because

the filling goes through BAM::OnAskForValuesToFill.

entry.title: Optimize encoding upload requests
entry.content:
Let R = #renderer_forms and B = #browser_form_fields



Previously FormStructure::EncodeFormFieldsForUpload used to take an

optional signature parameter and ignore all fields with a different

signature. This runs over all calls to the function in O(R * B).

to be considered so that all fields passed to the function have the

same signature to be considered. This reduces the worst case complexity

to O(B * log(B)) because of prior sorting.

entry.title: [Printing] Implement WebPrintJob::onjobstatechange event
entry.content:
The state transition graph looks as follows:

* A job from a resolved promise is created in kPreliminary state;

* Once this job is acknowledged by the printing pipeline, it moves

either to kPending (if positive) or kAborted (if negative);

* Once printing actually starts, it moves from kPending to kProcessing

* Eventually kProcessing resolves to either kComplete or kAborted.



There's also a state that represents canceled jobs (kCanceled) -- it's

present, but currently unused.

entry.title: [css-images-4] Implement unprefixed cross-fade().
entry.content:
This is similar to -webkit-cross-fade(), but differs in that it

has a different syntax, and supports more (or less) than two images.

It also supports cross-fading against a solid color, which we implement

internally as a gradient for simplicity. (This may not be optimal for

memory or performance, but it should do for now.)



We do not implement parts of the spec that are not yet written

but will be, in particular simplification at computed value time.



The functionality is behind a new runtime flag CSSCrossFade,

which is set to experimental as usual.

entry.title: Remove use of hinted font in FontCache font instantation
entry.content:
Hinted fonts ("screen fonts" vs "printer fonts" in Mac OS lingo) are

currently used in FontCache only when antialiasing is disabled in web

tests and in all other cases we use printer fonts in FontCache, compare

[1]. However, properties screenFont and printerFont are deprecated in

AppKit, compare [2].



Disable used of printer fonts in the remaining cases we had used them,

in testing.



This CL removes hinting usage and deprecated AppKit API calls. Since

hinting is only enabled in some Layout tests, this change should not

affect any web pages.
